Turn it into something reproducible (above-board)

If you want to test this properly, run a simple protocol:

1. Consent + frame
    * “Want to try a quick experiment to boost consistency?”
2. Pick one cue
    * e.g., “same breath, same motion, pick one spot on the board”
3. State set (1–2 minutes)
    * quick rhythm + light hype (keep it positive, not confusing)
4. Commitment
    * short, explicit: “Let’s aim for X in a row”
5. Rep block
    * 10–15 throws with only that one cue; minimal chatter
6. Debrief
    * “What felt different? Keep that.”

Measure it

* Baseline: how many in a row before
* After setup: best of 3 attempts
* Repeat across days/people

If it’s real, you’ll see average improvement across runs—not just a single spike.

⸻

Guardrails (so it scales)

* Be explicit about the experiment (no covert steering)
* Don’t overstack cues (one or two levers at a time)
* Track outcomes (avoid “I remember the hits”)
* Let people opt out (keeps trust intact)

